DataElementConcept.preferredName: Urinary System Findings Domain Urinary System Findings Specimen Type
DataElementConcept.preferredDefinition: A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to urinary system findings._The type of material sample used for urinary system testing.

ObjectClass.preferredDefinition: A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to urinary system findings.

Concepts.definition: A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to urinary system findings.

Property.preferredDefinition: The type of material sample used for urinary system testing.

Concepts.definition: The type of material sample used for urinary system testing.

ConceptualDomain.preferredDefinition: An organizational header for concepts representing mostly abstract entities.

DataElementConcept.changeDescription: Created for CTSU/NRDS Rave Glib. 7.23.19 mc

ValueDomain.preferredName: CDISC SDTM Specimen Type Terminology Type
ValueDomain.preferredDefinition: Terminology associated with the specimen type codelist of the Clinical Data Interchange Standards Consortium (CDISC) Study Data Tabulation Model (SDTM)._Something distinguishable as an identifiable class based on common qualities.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The liquid secreted by the sweat glands, having a salty taste and a pH that varies from 4.5 to 7.5. Sweat produced by the eccrine sweat glands is clear with a faint characteristic odor, and contains water, sodium chloride, and traces of albumin, urea, and other compounds. Its composition varies with many factors, e.g., fluid intake, external temperature and humidity, and some hormonal activity. Sweat produced by the larger, deeper, apocrine sweat glands of the axillae contains, in addition, organic material which on bacterial decomposition produces an offensive odor.

Concepts.definition: The liquid secreted by the sweat glands, having a salty taste and a pH that varies from 4.5 to 7.5. Sweat produced by the eccrine sweat glands is clear with a faint characteristic odor, and contains water, sodium chloride, and traces of albumin, urea, and other compounds. Its composition varies with many factors, e.g., fluid intake, external temperature and humidity, and some hormonal activity. Sweat produced by the larger, deeper, apocrine sweat glands of the axillae contains, in addition, organic material which on bacterial decomposition produces an offensive odor.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A yellowish substance produced during bacterial inflammation. It contains necrotic cells and cells fighting the infection.

Concepts.definition: A yellowish substance produced during bacterial inflammation. It contains necrotic cells and cells fighting the infection.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The watery fluid in the mouth made by the salivary glands. Saliva moistens food to help digestion and it helps protect the mouth against infections.

Concepts.definition: The watery fluid in the mouth made by the salivary glands. Saliva moistens food to help digestion and it helps protect the mouth against infections.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A slightly alkaline fluid produced by the prostate gland. It contributes 20-30% of the total volume of seminal fluid.

Concepts.definition: A slightly alkaline fluid produced by the prostate gland. It contributes 20-30% of the total volume of seminal fluid.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The tissue that lines the wall of the thoracic cavity and the surface of the lungs.

Concepts.definition: The tissue that lines the wall of the thoracic cavity and the surface of the lungs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fluid that is ordinarily present in the pleural space. It allows for normal movement of the lungs during respiration.

Concepts.definition: The fluid that is ordinarily present in the pleural space. It allows for normal movement of the lungs during respiration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A plasma sample that is prepared from whole blood, which has undergone a number of centrifugation steps to concentrate the amount of platelets.

Concepts.definition: A plasma sample that is prepared from whole blood, which has undergone a number of centrifugation steps to concentrate the amount of platelets.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A plasma sample that is prepared from whole blood, which has undergone a number of centrifugation steps to decrease the amount of platelets.

Concepts.definition: A plasma sample that is prepared from whole blood, which has undergone a number of centrifugation steps to decrease the amount of platelets.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: platelet. An irregularly shaped disklike cytoplasmic fragment of a megakaryocyte that is shed in the marrow sinus and subsequently found in the peripheral blood where it functions in clotting. A platelet contains granules in the central part (granulomere) and, peripherally, clear protoplasm (hyalomere), but no definite nucleus; is about one-third to one-half the size of an erythrocyte; and contains no hemoglobin. (STED98)

Concepts.definition: An irregular, disc-shaped element in the blood that assists in blood clotting. Platelets are not blood cells, they are fragments of large bone marrow cells called megakaryocytes.

ValueMeaning.administrativeNotes: 9/20/22 Changed PV in Biomarker Name VD to Platelet (was previously Platelet Count, which is C51951). Then made a new Platelet Count PV for Biomarker Name VD. mr;

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Plasma is the fluid (noncellular) portion of the circulating blood, as distinguished from the serum that is the fluid portion of the blood obtained by removal of the fibrin clot and blood cells after coagulation.

Concepts.definition: Plasma is the fluid (noncellular) portion of the circulating blood, as distinguished from the serum that is the fluid portion of the blood obtained by removal of the fibrin clot and blood cells after coagulation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The small amount of fluid that is generated in the abdominal cavity to lubricate the peritoneum.

Concepts.definition: The small amount of fluid that is generated in the abdominal cavity to lubricate the peritoneum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A peripheral blood cell with a single nucleus. This category includes lymphocytes and monocytes.

Concepts.definition: A peripheral blood cell with a single nucleus. This category includes lymphocytes and monocytes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The cutaneous plate on the dorsal surface of the distal end of a finger or toe.

Concepts.definition: The cutaneous plate on the dorsal surface of the distal end of a finger or toe.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Tissue responsible for the body movements and the shape and size changes of internal organs.  Muscle tissue is composed of specialized contractile cells.  There are two types of muscle tissue recognized: striated and smooth muscle.  The striated muscle tissue is further subdivided into skeletal, visceral striated, and cardiac muscle.

Concepts.definition: Tissue responsible for the body movements and the shape and size changes of internal organs.  Muscle tissue is composed of specialized contractile cells.  There are two types of muscle tissue recognized: striated and smooth muscle.  The striated muscle tissue is further subdivided into skeletal, visceral striated, and cardiac muscle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The viscous secretion of mucous membranes. It contains mucin, white blood cells, water, inorganic salts, and exfoliated cells.

Concepts.definition: The thick fluid secreted by the mucus glands in the aerodigestive tract and the vagina.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Large, phagocytic mononuclear leukocytes produced in the vertebrate bone marrow and released into the blood; contain a large, oval or somewhat indented nucleus surrounded by voluminous cytoplasm and numerous organelles.

Concepts.definition: Large, phagocytic mononuclear leukocytes produced in the vertebrate bone marrow and released into the blood; contain a large, oval or somewhat indented nucleus surrounded by voluminous cytoplasm and numerous organelles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The discharged blood from the uterus during the reproductive years. The discharge occurs approximately once a month.

Concepts.definition: The discharged blood from the uterus during the reproductive years. The discharge occurs approximately once a month.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The newborn's first intestinal discharge. It is a dark-green, thick substance composed of mucus, intestinal secretions, hair, and intestinal mucosa cells.

Concepts.definition: The newborn's first intestinal discharge. It is a dark-green, thick substance composed of mucus, intestinal secretions, hair, and intestinal mucosa cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The cellular debris and fluid produced by lysis of a cell.

Concepts.definition: The cellular debris and fluid produced by lysis of a cell.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The air that moves out of the chest during expiration. It contains a higher percentage of carbon dioxide and a lower percentage of oxygen compared to the inhaled air.

Concepts.definition: The air that moves out of the chest during expiration. It contains a higher percentage of carbon dioxide and a lower percentage of oxygen compared to the inhaled air.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Expired air that has been condensed.

Concepts.definition: Expired air that has been condensed.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Material, such as purulent and nonpurulent fluid, cells, or cellular debris, which has escaped from blood vessels and has been deposited in tissues or on tissue surfaces, usually as a result of inflammation.  An exudate, in contrast to a transudate, is characterized by a relatively high protein content.

Concepts.definition: Material, such as purulent and nonpurulent fluid, cells, or cellular debris, which has escaped from blood vessels and has been deposited in tissues or on tissue surfaces, usually as a result of inflammation.  An exudate, in contrast to a transudate, is characterized by a relatively high protein content.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Cell specialized for oxygen transport, having a high concentration of hemoglobin in the cytoplasm and little else; biconcave, anucleate discs, 7nm diameter in mammals.

Concepts.definition: A blood cell specialized for oxygen transport, having a high concentration of hemoglobin in the cytoplasm. They are biconcave, anucleate discs, with a 6-8um diameter in humans.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Cells that cover the surface of the body and line its cavities.

Concepts.definition: Any of the cells of the epithelium, which covers the body and lines its cavities and glands.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The epithelial portion of the skin (cutis). It consists of the following layers: stratum corneum (horny layer), stratum granulosum (granular layer), stratum spinosum (prickle cell layer), and stratum basale (basal cell layer).

Concepts.definition: The epithelial portion of the skin (cutis). It consists of the following layers: stratum corneum (horny layer), stratum granulosum (granular layer), stratum spinosum (prickle cell layer), and stratum basale (basal cell layer).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Stomach contents that have returned to the mouth or are ejected beyond the mouth.

Concepts.definition: Gastrointestinal contents that have returned to the mouth or are ejected beyond the mouth.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Normal or abnormal secretions expelled from a body location.

Concepts.definition: Normal or abnormal secretions expelled from a body location.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fluid which runs through a dialysis machine and captures, for discard or analysis, the excess water and waste from the blood stream through diffusion and ultrafiltration.

Concepts.definition: The fluid which runs through a dialysis machine and captures, for discard or analysis, the excess water and waste from the blood stream through diffusion and ultrafiltration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The cells and connective tissue from the inner layer of the two main layers of the skin. The dermis has connective tissue, blood vessels, oil and sweat glands, nerves, hair follicles, and other structures. It is made up of a thin upper layer called the papillary dermis, and a thick lower layer called the reticular dermis.

Concepts.definition: The lower layer of the skin containing connective tissue, blood vessels, oil and sweat glands, nerves, hair follicles and other structures.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The clear portion of the blood that remains after the removal of the blood cells and the clotting proteins from umbilical cord blood.

Concepts.definition: The clear portion of the blood that remains after the removal of the blood cells and the clotting proteins from umbilical cord blood.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Blood present in the umbilical vessels at the time of delivery. If cryopreserved at birth, cord blood can serve as a source of hematopoietic progenitor cells for transplantation to a patient later diagnosed and treated for a hematopoietic disorder.

Concepts.definition: Blood present in the umbilical vessels at the time of delivery. If cryopreserved at birth, cord blood can serve as a source of hematopoietic progenitor cells for transplantation to a patient later diagnosed and treated for a hematopoietic disorder.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Updated VM to use current NCIt definition. mc 10/28/19

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A thick, protein-rich substance secreted by the breasts during the second half of pregnancy and for a few days after birth before the breast milk comes in. It contains antibodies which serve to give the baby protection from disease and also has a laxative effect on the colon which helps to expel the plug of meconium and facilitate the establishment of normal bowel movements.

Concepts.definition: A thick, protein-rich substance secreted by the breasts during the second half of pregnancy and for a few days after birth before the breast milk comes in. It contains antibodies which serve to give the baby protection from disease and also has a laxative effect on the colon which helps to expel the plug of meconium and facilitate the establishment of normal bowel movements.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A metastatic cancer cell found in the peripheral blood.

Concepts.definition: A metastatic cancer cell found in the peripheral blood.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The watery fluid, consisting of vulvar gland, endometrium, and oviduct secretions, cervical mucus, vaginal wall plasma transudate, exfoliated cells, and bacterial and immune cell products, that hydrates and forms an antimicrobial barrier for the mucosa of the lower female genital tract.

Concepts.definition: The watery fluid, consisting of vulvar gland, endometrium, and oviduct secretions, cervical mucus, vaginal wall plasma transudate, exfoliated cells, and bacterial and immune cell products, that hydrates and forms an antimicrobial barrier for the mucosa of the lower female genital tract.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A soft yellow wax secreted by glands in the ear canal.

Concepts.definition: A soft yellow wax secreted by glands in the ear canal.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fluid that is contained within the brain ventricles, the subarachnoid space and the central canal of the spinal cord.

Concepts.definition: The fluid that is contained within the brain ventricles, the subarachnoid space and the central canal of the spinal cord.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The contents of the stomach that may include undigested food mixed with juices secreted by the gastric mucosal glands.

Concepts.definition: The contents of the stomach that may include undigested food mixed with juices secreted by the gastric mucosal glands.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Liquid and semi liquid substances produced by living organisms to fulfill specific functions or excreted as waste; does not include hormones or enzymes.

Concepts.definition: Material produced by living organisms; it can be a necessary constituent of, or product of an organismal process.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The striated muscle tissue of the heart enveloped by the epicardium and the endocardium.

Concepts.definition: The striated muscle tissue of the heart enveloped by the epicardium and the endocardium.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Plasma that has been isolated from capillary blood.

Concepts.definition: Plasma that has been isolated from capillary blood.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A mixture of arterial blood, venous blood and interstitial fluid, which is found in the capillaries.

Concepts.definition: A mixture of arterial blood, venous blood and interstitial fluid, which is found in the capillaries.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Accumulated material from the secretions of an organ. It is solid and representative examples include gallbladder stones, kidney stones, and salivary gland stones. (NCI)

Concepts.definition: Accumulated material from the secretions of an organ. It is solid and representative examples include gallbladder stones, kidney stones, and salivary gland stones.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The middle layer of an anticoagulated blood specimen following separation by centrifugation. It contains most of the white blood cells and platelets.

Concepts.definition: The middle layer of an anticoagulated blood specimen following separation by centrifugation. It contains most of the white blood cells and platelets.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Milk produced by female humans for the purpose of feeding their young.

Concepts.definition: Milk produced by female mammals for the purpose of feeding their young.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The tissue occupying the spaces of bone. It consists of blood vessel sinuses and a network of hematopoietic cells which give rise to the red cells, white cells, and megakaryocytes.

Concepts.definition: The tissue occupying the spaces of bone. It consists of blood vessel sinuses and a network of hematopoietic cells which give rise to the red cells, white cells, and megakaryocytes.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Concept annotation added for UPitt/TCGA.  Ylu, 02/03/2015.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Connective tissue that forms the skeletal components of the body.

Concepts.definition: The structural organ comprised of specialized connective tissue that forms the skeletal components of the body.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Updated concept definition with current NCIt. 4.5.18 mc

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A liquid tissue; its major function is to transport oxygen throughout the body. It also supplies the tissues with nutrients, removes waste products, and contains various components of the immune system defending the body against infection. Several hormones also travel in the blood.

Concepts.definition: A liquid tissue; its major function is to transport oxygen throughout the body. It also supplies the tissues with nutrients, removes waste products, and contains various components of the immune system defending the body against infection. Several hormones also travel in the blood.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An emulsifying agent produced in the LIVER and secreted into the DUODENUM. Its composition includes BILE ACIDS AND SALTS, CHOLESTEROL, and ELECTROLYTES. It aids DIGESTION of fats in the duodenum.

Concepts.definition: Fluid composed of waste products, bile acids, salts, cholesterol, and electrolytes. It is secreted by the liver parenchyma and stored in the gallbladder.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Fatty tissue which is deposited in the inner lining of the arterial wall.

Concepts.definition: Fatty tissue which is deposited in the inner lining of the arterial wall.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Blood present in the umbilical arteries at the time of delivery.

Concepts.definition: Blood present in the umbilical arteries at the time of delivery.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Blood found in arteries, generally oxygenated blood which is transported with nutrients to body tissues through the arterial system. The exception is blood within the pulmonary artery which carries deoxygenated blood to the lungs.

Concepts.definition: Blood found in arteries, generally oxygenated blood which is transported with nutrients to body tissues through the arterial system. The exception is blood within the pulmonary artery which carries deoxygenated blood to the lungs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The clear, watery fluid which fills the anterior and posterior chambers of the eye. It has a refractive index lower than the crystalline lens, which it surrounds, and is involved in the metabolism of the cornea and the crystalline lens. (Cline et al., Dictionary of Visual Science, 4th ed, p319)

Concepts.definition: The watery fluid which is present in the anterior and posterior chambers of the eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fluid within the amniotic cavity which surrounds and protects the developing embryo.  It is initially produced by the amnion and then later by the lungs and kidneys.  The amount at term normally varies from 500 to 2000 ml.

Concepts.definition: The fluid within the amniotic cavity which surrounds and protects the developing embryo. It is initially produced by the amnion and then later by the lungs and kidneys. The amount at term normally varies from 500 to 2000 ml.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The gas located in the alveolus of the lungs, which takes part in gas exchange with the blood in the pulmonary capillaries.

Concepts.definition: The gas located in the alveolus of the lungs, which takes part in gas exchange with the blood in the pulmonary capillaries.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Connective tissue composed of fat cells lodged in the meshes of areolar tissue.

Concepts.definition: A specialized form of connective tissue consisting primarily of adipocytes (fat cells), surrounded by a meshwork of collagen fibers.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The nerve tissue forming the bulk of the deep parts of the brain and the superficial parts of the spinal cord.  It is composed of nerve cell processes, i.e. extensions (axons), which connect various grey matter areas of the brain to each other and carry nerve impulses to and from the nerve cell bodies within the central nervous system (neurons).  Cerebral and spinal white matter does not contain dendrites.  White matter is distinguished in that it is composed of axonal nerve fibers covered by a myelin sheath.

Concepts.definition: The nerve tissue forming the bulk of the deep parts of the brain and the superficial parts of the spinal cord. It is composed of nerve cell processes, i.e. extensions (axons), which connect various grey matter areas of the brain to each other and carry nerve impulses to and from the nerve cell bodies within the central nervous system (neurons). Cerebral and spinal white matter does not contain dendrites. White matter is distinguished in that it is composed of axonal nerve fibers covered by a myelin sheath.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A clear, avascular, gelatinous body that occupies the posterior chamber of the eye. It is bounded by the retina except anteriorly where it lies adjacent to the lens and iris.

Concepts.definition: The clear colorless transparent jelly that fills the posterior chamber of the eyeball.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Plasma that has been isolated from venous blood.

Concepts.definition: Plasma that has been isolated from venous blood.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Blood present in the umbilical vein at the time of delivery.

Concepts.definition: Blood present in the umbilical vein at the time of delivery.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Blood carried in veins, generally deoxygenated blood containing urea and other waste products which is transported through the venous system to the heart and lungs. The exception is blood within the pulmonary vein which is oxygenated and travels from the lungs to the left atrium of the heart.

Concepts.definition: Blood carried in veins, generally deoxygenated blood containing urea and other waste products which is transported through the venous system to the heart and lungs. The exception is blood within the pulmonary vein which is oxygenated and travels from the lungs to the left atrium of the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fluid that is excreted by the kidneys.  It is stored in the bladder and discharged through the urethra.

Concepts.definition: The fluid that is excreted by the kidneys.  It is stored in the bladder and discharged through the urethra.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tissue sample, or entire tumor that is removed for microscopic examination.

Concepts.definition: Tissue sample that contains an abnormal cellular infiltrate forming a solid mass. The abnormal cellular component can be benign or malignant. Tumor samples are obtained for microscopic examination and/or molecular analysis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fluid that passes through the wall of the veins and capillaries to the surrounding tissues because of increased intravascular pressure. It has low protein content.

Concepts.definition: The fluid that passes through the wall of the veins and capillaries to the surrounding tissues because of increased intravascular pressure. It has low protein content.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An anatomical structure consisting of similarly specialized cells and intercellular matrix, aggregated according to genetically determined spatial relationships, performing a specific function.

Concepts.definition: An anatomical structure consisting of similarly specialized cells and intercellular matrix, aggregated according to genetically determined spatial relationships, performing a specific function.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A viscid fluid secreted by the synovial membrane, serving as a lubricant.

Concepts.definition: A viscid fluid secreted by the synovial membrane, serving as a lubricant.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A heterogeneous and variable aggregate of body fluids, tissues, cells, microorganisms, and other materials that are collected from a swab biospecimen collection procedure.

Concepts.definition: A heterogeneous and variable aggregate of body fluids, tissues, cells, microorganisms, and other materials that are collected from a swab biospecimen collection procedure.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a serum or plasma sample.

Concepts.definition: The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a serum or plasma sample.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a serum sample.

Concepts.definition: The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a serum sample.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a pleural fluid sample.

Concepts.definition: The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a pleural fluid sample.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a cerebrospinal fluid sample.

Concepts.definition: The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a cerebrospinal fluid sample.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a plasma sample.

Concepts.definition: The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a plasma sample.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Striated muscles are appendicular and axial muscles typically connected at either or both ends to the bony skeleton of the body.  Striated muscle fibers contain a highly organized, contractile cytoskeletal apparatus with a striated microscopic appearance; muscle contraction is typically under voluntary control.

Concepts.definition: Striated muscles are appendicular and axial muscles typically connected at either or both ends to the bony skeleton of the body.  Striated muscle fibers contain a highly organized, contractile cytoskeletal apparatus with a striated microscopic appearance; muscle contraction is typically under voluntary control.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The material discharged from the bowel during defecation.  It consists of undigested food, intestinal mucus, epithelial cells, and bacteria.

Concepts.definition: The material discharged from the bowel during defecation.  It consists of undigested food, intestinal mucus, epithelial cells, and bacteria.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Material containing mucus, cellular debris, microorganisms and sometimes blood or pus.  It is ejected through the mouth from the lungs, bronchi, and trachea.

Concepts.definition: Material containing mucus, cellular debris, microorganisms and sometimes blood or pus.  It is ejected through the mouth from the lungs, bronchi, and trachea.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The male reproductive cell that is formed in the testicle. A sperm consists of a head, a body, and a tail that provides propulsion.

Concepts.definition: The male reproductive cell that is formed in the testicle. A sperm consists of a head, a body, and a tail that provides propulsion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Refers to muscle, fat, fibrous tissue, blood vessels, or other supporting tissue of the body.

Concepts.definition: A general term comprising tissue that is not hardened or calcified; including muscle, fat, blood vessels, nerves, tendons, ligaments and fascia.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fluid that is abnormally collected in localized areas of damaged tissue within the body, usually composed of living and dead white blood cells, bacteria, and dead tissue.

Concepts.definition: The fluid that is abnormally collected in localized areas of damaged tissue within the body, usually composed of living and dead white blood cells, bacteria, and dead tissue.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Involuntary muscle tissue of the internal organs. It is composed of elongated muscle cells or fibers that are not arranged in a striated pattern and form layers of muscle tissue. The smooth muscle cells contain a contractile apparatus composed of thin and thick filaments and a cytoskeleton composed of intermediate filaments.

Concepts.definition: Involuntary muscle tissue of the internal organs. It is composed of elongated muscle cells or fibers that are not arranged in a striated pattern and form layers of muscle tissue. The smooth muscle cells contain a contractile apparatus composed of thin and thick filaments and a cytoskeleton composed of intermediate filaments.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A white secretion of the sebaceous glands of the foreskin.

Concepts.definition: A white secretion of the sebaceous glands of the foreskin.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Tissue composed of three layers- epidermis, dermis and subcutis which protect underlying muscles and organs. Skin is used for insulation, vitamin D production, sensation, and excretion through sweat.

Concepts.definition: Tissue composed of three layers- epidermis, dermis and subcutis which protect underlying muscles and organs. Skin is used for insulation, vitamin D production, sensation, and excretion through sweat.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Striated muscles that are under voluntary control of the organism. They are connected at either or both ends to a bone and are utilized for locomotion and other movements. (NCI)

Concepts.definition: Striated muscles that are under voluntary control of the organism.  They are connected at either or both ends to a bone and are utilized for locomotion and other movements.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The non-cellular portion of the circulating blood, with or without the clotting proteins present.

Concepts.definition: The non-cellular portion of the circulating blood, with or without the clotting proteins present.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The clear liquid part of the blood that remains after blood cells and clotting proteins have been removed.

Concepts.definition: The clear portion of the blood that remains after the removal of the blood cells and the clotting proteins.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Seminal fluid

Concepts.definition: Part of the ejaculated fluid. It contains secretions from the seminal vesicles, Cowper's gland, and prostate gland.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The thick, whitish secretion of the male reproductive organs. It is composed of spermatozoa in their nutrient plasma, secretions from the prostate, seminal vesicles, and various other glands, epithelial cells, and minor constituents.

Concepts.definition: The thick, whitish secretion of the male reproductive organs. It is composed of spermatozoa in their nutrient plasma, secretions from the prostate, seminal vesicles, and various other glands, epithelial cells, and minor constituents.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A thick, oily substance produced by the sebaceous glands located in the dermis.

Concepts.definition: A thick, oily substance produced by the sebaceous glands located in the dermis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Pulmonary surfactant lines the lung epithelium and lowers surface tension to prevent collapse at end-expiration. Deficiency of pulmonary surfactant results in respiratory distress syndrome (RDS) in premature infants. Lung surfactant is synthesized in alveolar type II cells, stored in lamellar bodies and secreted via exocytosis.

Concepts.definition: Pulmonary surfactant lines the lung epithelium and lowers surface tension to prevent collapse at end-expiration. Deficiency of pulmonary surfactant results in respiratory distress syndrome (RDS) in premature infants. Lung surfactant is synthesized in alveolar type II cells, stored in lamellar bodies and secreted via exocytosis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: (lim-FAT-ik) The clear fluid that travels through the lymphatic system and carries cells that help fight infections and other diseases. Also called lymph.

Concepts.definition: A clear, transparent, sometimes faintly yellow and slightly opalescent fluid that is collected from the tissues throughout the body, flows in the lymphatic vessels (through the lymph nodes), and is eventually added to the venous blood circulation. Lymph consists of a clear liquid portion, varying numbers of white blood cells (chiefly lymphocytes), and a few red blood cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Vaginal discharge occurring during the post-partum period. It consists of a mixture of blood, mucus, and placental remnants.

Concepts.definition: Vaginal discharge occurring during the post-partum period. It consists of a mixture of blood, mucus, and placental remnants.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Blood cells that are devoid of hemoglobin, capable of ameboid motion and phagocytosis, and act as the principal components of the immune system.

Concepts.definition: Blood cells that are devoid of hemoglobin, capable of ameboid motion and phagocytosis, and act as the principal components of the immune system.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Fluid introduced into, and collected from, a body cavity by lavage procedure.

Concepts.definition: Fluid introduced into, and collected from, a body cavity by lavage procedure.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The keratin-producing cells of the epidermis.  They are the predominant cells of the epidermis that form in the deep basal layer of the stratified epithelium of the epidermis.  They gradually migrate upward to the cornified layer of the epidermis undergoing characteristic changes.

Concepts.definition: The keratin-producing cells of the epidermis.  They are the predominant cells of the epidermis that form in the deep basal layer of the stratified epithelium of the epidermis.  They gradually migrate upward to the cornified layer of the epidermis undergoing characteristic changes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A specific individual microbe and its genetically identical progeny separated on a single occasion from a sample taken from a host or culture system.

Concepts.definition: A specific individual microbe and its genetically identical progeny separated on a single occasion from a sample taken from a host or culture system.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The extracellular fluid component found in the spaces between tissues. This excludes plasma and transcellular fluid.

Concepts.definition: The extracellular fluid component found in the spaces between tissues. This excludes plasma and transcellular fluid.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The liquid, solid or semi-solid lying below a liquid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a serum sample.

Concepts.definition: The liquid, solid or semi-solid lying below a liquid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a serum sample.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The liquid, solid or semi-solid lying below a liquid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a pleural fluid sample.

Concepts.definition: The liquid, solid or semi-solid lying below a liquid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a pleural fluid sample.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The liquid, solid or semi-solid lying below a liquid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a plasma sample.

Concepts.definition: The liquid, solid or semi-solid lying below a liquid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a plasma sample.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tube-like invagination of the epidermis from which the hair shaft develops and into which the sebaceous glands open; the follicle is lined by a cellular inner and outer root sheath of epidermal origin and is invested with a fibrous sheath derived from the dermis.

Concepts.definition: A tube-like invagination of the epidermis from which the hair shaft develops and into which the sebaceous glands open; the follicle is lined by a cellular inner and outer root sheath of epidermal origin and is invested with a fibrous sheath derived from the dermis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The filamentous outgrowth of the epidermis.

Concepts.definition: The filamentous outgrowth of the epidermis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fluid produced by the stomach glands, composed of gastric acids and enzymes.

Concepts.definition: The fluid produced by the stomach glands, composed of gastric acids and enzymes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Immature erythrocytes that have just undergone extrusion of their cell nucleus. They still contain some organelles that gradually decrease in number as the cells mature.

Concepts.definition: Immature erythrocytes that have just undergone extrusion of their cell nucleus. They still contain some organelles that gradually decrease in number as the cells mature.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The dialysis fluid which is collected from the peritoneal space and captures, for discard or analysis, the excess water and waste from the blood stream through diffusion and ultrafiltration. (NCI)

Concepts.definition: The dialysis fluid which is collected from the peritoneal space and captures, for discard or analysis, the excess water and waste from the blood stream through diffusion and ultrafiltration. (NCI)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A cell sample collected and compacted by centrifugation of a liquid suspension.

Concepts.definition: A cell sample collected and compacted by centrifugation of a liquid suspension.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any cell with a single nucleus found in the bone marrow, for example lymphocytes, monocytes, mesenchymal stem cells and hematopoietic progenitor cells.

Concepts.definition: Any cell with a single nucleus found in the bone marrow, for example lymphocytes, monocytes, mesenchymal stem cells and hematopoietic progenitor cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Material that has settled out of solution in urine.

Concepts.definition: Material that has settled out of solution in urine.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The de-oxygenated blood flowing into the right side of the heart, composed of a mixture of venous blood from the entirety of the systemic circulation.

Concepts.definition: The de-oxygenated blood flowing into the right side of the heart, composed of a mixture of venous blood from the entirety of the systemic circulation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A specimen type containing serum, plasma or blood.

Concepts.definition: A specimen type containing serum, plasma or blood.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fluid collected from the lumen of the trachea.

Concepts.definition: The fluid collected from the lumen of the trachea.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The mucous membrane comprising the inner layer of the uterine wall; it consists of a simple columnar epithelium and a lamina propria that contains simple tubular uterine glands. The structure, thickness, and state of the endometrium undergo marked change with the menstrual cycle.

Concepts.definition: The mucous membrane comprising the inner layer of the uterine wall; it consists of a simple columnar epithelium and a lamina propria that contains simple tubular uterine glands. The structure, thickness, and state of the endometrium undergo marked change with the menstrual cycle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fluid that is produced from the movement of whole blood across a semipermeable membrane in response to a pressure gradient, removing blood cells and large proteins.

Concepts.definition: The fluid that is produced from the movement of whole blood across a semipermeable membrane in response to a pressure gradient, removing blood cells and large proteins.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Capillary blood collected from a puncture site that has been warmed or treated with creams containing a hyperemic or vasodilatory agent to increase arterial blood flow.

Concepts.definition: Capillary blood collected from a puncture site that has been warmed or treated with creams containing a hyperemic or vasodilatory agent to increase arterial blood flow.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of tear produced in response to negative and positive emotions; contains higher amounts of proteins and stress-related hormones in comparison to other tear types.

Concepts.definition: A type of tear produced in response to negative and positive emotions; contains higher amounts of proteins and stress-related hormones in comparison to other tear types.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of tear produced in response to irritation from foreign particles, vapors, bright lights, or peppery substances; contains higher amounts of antibodies in comparison to other tear types.

Concepts.definition: A type of tear produced in response to irritation from foreign particles, vapors, bright lights, or peppery substances; contains higher amounts of antibodies in comparison to other tear types.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of tear that is spread across the surface of the eye at regular intervals with blinking, coating the eyes to keep them moist.

Concepts.definition: A type of tear that is spread across the surface of the eye at regular intervals with blinking, coating the eyes to keep them moist.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A fluid containing oils, mucin, and proteins, which is secreted by the lacrimal gland and cleans and lubricates the eye.

Concepts.definition: A fluid containing oils, mucin, and proteins, which is secreted by the lacrimal gland and cleans and lubricates the eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A connective tissue cell that makes and secretes collagen proteins.

Concepts.definition: A connective tissue cell that makes and secretes collagen proteins.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of immune cell that is made in the bone marrow and is found in the blood and in lymph tissue. The two main types of lymphocytes are B lymphocytes and T lymphocytes. B lymphocytes make antibodies, and T lymphocytes help kill tumor cells and help control immune responses. A lymphocyte is a type of white blood cell.

Concepts.definition: White blood cells formed in the body's lymphoid tissue. The nucleus is round or ovoid with coarse, irregularly clumped chromatin while the cytoplasm is typically pale blue with azurophilic (if any) granules. Most lymphocytes can be classified as either T or B (with subpopulations of each); those with characteristics of neither major class are called null cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of leukocyte with a multilobed nucleus and cytoplasmic granules. The unique morphology of the nucleus has led to their also being known as polymorphonuclear leukocytes (PMLs or PMNs). Granulocytes are subdivided according to the staining properties of their granules into eosinophils (red with acidic dye), basophils (blue with basic dye), and neutrophils (not amenable to staining with either acidic or basic dyes).

Concepts.definition: A type of leukocyte with a multilobed nucleus and cytoplasmic granules. The unique morphology of the nucleus has led to their also being known as polymorphonuclear leukocytes (PMLs or PMNs). Granulocytes are subdivided according to the staining properties of their granules into eosinophils (red with acidic dye), basophils (blue with basic dye), and neutrophils (not amenable to staining with either acidic or basic dyes).

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Changed to current NCIt definition per NMDP request. mc 9/9/2020

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of immune cell that has granules (small particles) with enzymes that can kill tumor cells or cells infected with a virus. A natural killer cell is a type of white blood cell.

Concepts.definition: Natural killer cells are cells that resemble large granular lymphocytes.  They do not express markers of either T or B cell lineage. They are positive for CD16, CD56, and CD 94.  These cells do possess Fc receptors for IgG and can kill target cells using antibody-dependent cell-mediated cytotoxicity. They can also use perforin to kill cells in the absence of antibody and killing may occur without previous sensitization.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a lavage fluid sample.

Concepts.definition: The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a lavage fluid sample.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fluid (acellular) portion of the circulating blood with retained clotting components from the cord blood of a newborn baby.

Concepts.definition: The fluid (acellular) portion of the circulating blood with retained clotting components from the cord blood of a newborn baby.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Aspirate from bone marrow.

Concepts.definition: Aspirate from bone marrow.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A specimen of bone marrow tissue obtained by using a relatively large diameter needle designed to acquire a core specimen.

Concepts.definition: A specimen of bone marrow tissue obtained by using a relatively large diameter needle designed to acquire a core specimen.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Endogenously generated droplets present in exhaled air, containing water and non-volatile material, which originate from the surfactant and respiratory tract lining fluid from the most distal airways.

Concepts.definition: Endogenously generated droplets present in exhaled air, containing water and non-volatile material, which originate from the surfactant and respiratory tract lining fluid from the most distal airways.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A plasma sample that is prepared from arterial blood.

Concepts.definition: A plasma sample that is prepared from arterial blood.
